        output='Based on the provided S-1 prospectus excerpts, here is the detailed disclosure regarding the company\'s "controlled company" status, Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas listing standards, and corporate governance independence requirements:\n\n### 1. "Controlled Company" Status and Rationale\nUpon the completion of the IPO, Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (listing under the symbol **SPCX** on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas) will qualify as a **"controlled company."** \n* **Voting Power:** Elon Musk will beneficially own a majority of the voting power of the outstanding common stock through his holdings of Class A and Class B common stock.\n* **Board Election Rights:** Under the company\'s charter, holders of Class B common stock (voting separately as a class) have the exclusive right to elect **51% of the total number of authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number), designated as "Class B Directors." Because Mr. Musk holds a majority of the Class B shares, he will unilaterally control the election of these directors and, consequently, the outcome of all matters requiring shareholder approval.\n* **Nasdaq Definition:** Under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas rules, a company where more than 50% of the voting power for director elections is held by an individual or group is classified as a "controlled company."\n\n### 2. Nasdaq Corporate Governance Exemptions\nAs a controlled company, SpaceX intends to rely on specific exemptions from Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance listing requirements. The company **will not be required to comply** with the following mandates:\n* **Board Independence:** Having a majority of the board of directors composed of independent directors.\n* **Nominating Committee:** Requiring director nominees to be selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed *entirely* of independent directors with a formal written charter.\n* **Compensation Committee:** Requiring the compensation committee to be composed *entirely* of independent directors with a formal written charter addressing its purpose and responsibilities.\n* **Performance Evaluations:** Conducting annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees.\n\n**Impact on Shareholders:** The prospectus explicitly warns that Class A shareholders will not have the same governance protections afforded to shareholders of companies subject to all standard Nasdaq corporate governance requirements. If the company ever ceases to be a "controlled company," it will be required to comply with all standard governance requirements within applicable transition periods.\n\n### 3. Retained Governance and Compliance Requirements\nDespite the controlled company exemptions, the company remains subject to several strict regulatory and listing requirements:\n* **Audit Committee Independence:** The audit committee must still be composed *entirely* of independent directors. \n* **Code of Ethics & Governance Guidelines:** The board will adopt a Code of Business Conduct and Ethics and Corporate Governance Guidelines compliant with SEC and Nasdaq rules. Waivers or amendments for executive officers/directors will be disclosed on the company\'s website (`www.spacex.com`).\n* **Clawback Policy:** The company will adopt a compensation recoupment (clawback) policy compliant with Nasdaq listing standards implementing SEC Rule 10D-1.\n* **Share Issuance Rules:** While the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC) does not require shareholder approval for issuing authorized shares, Nasdaq rules still mandate shareholder approval for issuances equal to or exceeding 20% of the outstanding voting power or common stock.\n\n### 4. Board Composition and Independence Determinations\nPost-IPO, the board will consist of **eight directors**, subject to annual elections.\n* **Class B Directors (Elected by Class B Stock):** Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek.\n* **Common Stock Directors (Elected by Class A & B Stock jointly):** Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson.\n* **Independence Determinations:** The board has determined that five directors meet the Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas independence standards: **Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, Donald Harrison, Steve Jurvetson, and Luke Nosek**.\n\n### 5. Committee Structures\n* **Audit Committee:** Expected members are **Randy Glein** (Chair) and **Steve Jurvetson**. Both qualify as independent under Rule 10A-3 and Nasdaq standards. Glein qualifies as an "audit committee financial expert." A third independent member will be identified within the one-year transition period allowed by Nasdaq.\n* **Compensation and Nominating Committee:** Expected members are **Ira Ehrenpreis** (Chair), **Antonio J. Gracias**, and **Luke Nosek**. \n  * *Exemption Reliance:* Because of the controlled company exemption, this committee is *not* required to be entirely independent. While Ehrenpreis and Nosek meet heightened independence standards (and qualify as "non-employee directors" under Rule 16b-3), the inclusion of Gracias means the committee does not consist solely of independent directors.\n  * *Historical Context:* Historically, the full board (and primarily Mr. Musk) made compensation decisions. \n\n### 6. Additional Governance Disclosures\n* **Renunciation of Corporate Opportunities:** The charter includes a provision renouncing any company interest or expectancy in business opportunities presented to board members, board observers, attendees, or their affiliates. These individuals have no duty to present such opportunities to SpaceX and may pursue them personally.\n* **Director Liability (TBOC):** Because the company will have voting common stock listed on a national exchange, Section 21.418 of the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC) will apply. This limits the liability of directors and officers for breach of duty regarding interested-party transactions, provided they comply with the safe harbors of Section 21.419.\n* **Risk Oversight:** The full board and its committees hold oversight responsibility for enterprise risk management, while executive management retains direct responsibility for day-to-day risk assessment and mitigation.',
