2026-06-09 23:27:08,684 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## SpaceX S-1: Nasdaq Controlled-Company Exemptions — Detailed Analysis\n\n### Where the Exemptions Are Disclosed\n\nThe controlled-company exemptions are disclosed in three locations within the S-1:\n\n1. **"Management — Controlled Company Exemption"** — the primary, dedicated section providing the full enumeration of exemptions relied upon.\n2. **"Risk Factors"** (beginning on page 26) — a risk-factor disclosure warning Class A shareholders that they will not receive the same governance protections as shareholders of companies subject to all standard Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements.\n3. **Prospectus Summary** — a summary table row titled "Controlled company" that cross-references the "Management — Controlled Company Exemption" and "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions" sections.\n\nNotably, the filing does **not** cite specific Nasdaq rule numbers (e.g., Rule 5615(c)); it refers generally to "the corporate governance rules of Nasdaq" and "Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules."\n\n---\n\n### Board-Level and Committee-Level Independence Requirements WAIVED\n\nSpaceX qualifies as a "controlled company" because Elon Musk will hold more than 50% of the voting power for the election of directors (through Class A and Class B common stock, with Class B holders having the exclusive right to elect 51% of authorized directors). SpaceX intends to rely on exemptions from the following four requirements:\n\n| # | Requirement Waived | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Majority Board Independence** | The requirement that a majority of the board of directors consist of independent directors. |\n| 2 | **Independent Nominating Committee** | The requirement that director nominees be selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed *entirely* of independent directors, with a formal written charter addressing the nominations process. |\n| 3 | **Independent Compensation Committee** | The requirement that the compensation committee be composed *entirely* of independent directors, with a formal written charter addressing the committee\'s purpose and responsibilities. |\n| 4 | **Committee Performance Evaluations** | The requirement to conduct annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees. |\n\n**Practical application:** SpaceX\'s combined Compensation and Nominating Committee is expected to include Ira Ehrenpreis (Chair, independent), Luke Nosek (independent), and Antonio J. Gracias (not independent). The filing explicitly states the committee charter will not address all requirements normally applicable to non-controlled companies.\n\n---\n\n### Requirements That REMAIN FULLY APPLICABLE (Not Waived)\n\nThe controlled-company exemption does **not** relieve SpaceX of the following obligations:\n\n| # | Requirement Retained | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Audit Committee — 100% Independence** | The audit committee must still be composed *entirely* of independent directors. The filing explicitly states: "As a controlled company, we will remain subject to rules that require us to have an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors." |\n| 2 | **Rule 10A-3 Compliance** | Audit committee members must meet the heightened independence standards of Rule 10A-3 under the Exchange Act. |\n| 3 | **Audit Committee Financial Expert** | At least one member must qualify as an "audit committee financial expert" under SEC rules implementing SOX Section 407 (Randy Glein is expected to serve in this role). |\n| 4 | **Audit Committee Written Charter** | A written charter must be maintained and posted on the company\'s website. |\n| 5 | **Related Person Transaction Policy** | The audit committee must adopt and enforce a written policy to review, approve, or disapprove related person transactions exceeding $120,000. |\n| 6 | **Code of Business Conduct and Ethics** | Must be adopted for employees, directors, and officers, with SEC/Nasdaq-compliant disclosure of waivers or amendments for executive officers/directors. |\n| 7 | **Corporate Governance Guidelines** | Must be adopted and posted on the company\'s website. |\n| 8 | **Clawback Policy** | A compensation recoupment policy compliant with Nasdaq listing standards implementing SEC Rule 10D-1 must be adopted. |\n| 9 | **Nasdaq Shareholder Approval Rules** | Nasdaq rules requiring shareholder approval for issuances equal to or exceeding 20% of outstanding voting power or common stock remain applicable. |\n| 10 | **Director Independence Determinations** | The board must still evaluate and determine which directors meet Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas independence standards. |\n\n---\n\n### Conditioning on Continuous Controlled-Company Status\n\n**Yes — every waiver is expressly conditioned on SpaceX maintaining controlled-company status continuously.** The filing states that SpaceX may elect to take advantage of these exemptions **"for as long as we remain a \'controlled company.\'"**\n\nIf SpaceX ceases to be a controlled company (e.g., if Elon Musk\'s voting power falls below 50%), the filing states:\n\n- SpaceX will be required to comply with **all** standard Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements, including majority board independence, fully independent compensation and nominating committees, and full committee charters.\n- Compliance must be achieved **"within the applicable transition periods"** provided by Nasdaq rules (the filing does not specify the exact duration of these transition periods but references standard exchange transition rules).\n- At that point, Class A shareholders would gain the same governance protections afforded to shareholders of non-controlled public companies.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe filing is explicit and comprehensive in its disclosure: four specific governance requirements are waived (majority board independence, independent nominating committee, independent compensation committee, and committee performance evaluations), while audit committee independence and all other SEC/Nasdaq baseline requirements remain fully in force. All waivers are contingent on continuous controlled-company status, and loss of that status triggers mandatory full compliance within applicable Nasdaq transition periods.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
